content.problemStatement:
- Imagine you're designing a page and want everything to follow the same look. Instead of telling each element what to do one by one, you can write a "style guide" just for that page. That's **Internal CSS**!

**How it works:**

- **It's a Style Sheet:** You write all your styling rules inside a `` tag.  
- **It Lives in the Head:** You place this `` tag in the `` section of your HTML file. Think of the head as the "brain" of your page, where all the behind-the-scenes rules are kept.  
- **It Affects the Whole Page:** Any styles you define here will apply to **all** the matching elements on that single HTML page.
---
**Syntax**\
Here's what it looks like in your code. You define which element you want to style (like `p` for paragraphs) and then list the style rules inside curly braces `{}`.
```sefwef


    /* This is a comment! */
    p {
      color: purple;
      font-size: 16px;
    }
    h1 {
      color: orange;
    }


```
Using Internal CSS is a big step up from inline styles because it keeps your code much cleaner and makes it easier to update the look of your page.

